column11: the Batch service upgrades each compute node in the pool. When a compute node is chosen for upgrade
column12: any tasks running on that node are removed from the node and returned to the queue to be rerun later (or on a different compute node). The node will be unavailable until the upgrade is complete. This operation results in temporarily reduced pool capacity as nodes are taken out of service to be upgraded. Although the Batch service tries to avoid upgrading all compute nodes at the same time
column13: it does not guarantee to do this (particularly on small pools); therefore
column14: the pool may be temporarily unavailable to run tasks. When this operation runs
column15: the pool state changes to upgrading. When all compute nodes have finished upgrading
column16: the pool state returns to active. While the upgrade is in progress
column17: the pool's currentOSVersion reflects the OS version that nodes are upgrading from
column18: and targetOSVersion reflects the OS version that nodes are upgrading to. Once the upgrade is complete
column19: currentOSVersion is updated to reflect the OS version now running on all nodes. This operation can only be invoked on pools created with the cloudServiceConfiguration property."]

column14: or a page blob. If the destination blob already exists
column15: it must be of the  same blob type as the source blob. Any existing destination blob will be  overwritten. The destination blob cannot be modified while a copy operation  is in progress.  When copying from a page blob
column16: the Blob service creates a destination page  blob of the source blob's length
column17: initially containing all zeroes. Then  the source page ranges are enumerated
column18: and non-empty ranges are copied.   For a block blob or an append blob
column19: the Blob service creates a committed  blob of zero length before returning from this operation. When copying  from a block blob
column20: all committed blocks and their block IDs are copied.  Uncommitted blocks are not copied. At the end of the copy operation
column21: the  destination blob will have the same committed block count as the source.  When copying from an append blob
column22: all committed blocks are copied. At the  end of the copy operation
column23: the destination blob will have the same committed  block count as the source.  For all blob types

column12: any tasks running on that node are removed from the node and returned to the queue to be rerun later (or on a different compute node). Although the Batch service tries to avoid upgrading all compute nodes at the same time
column13: it does not guarantee to do this (particularly on small pools); therefore
column14: the pool may be temporarily unavailable to run tasks. When this operation runs
column15: the pool state changes to upgrading. When all compute nodes have finished upgrading
column16: the pool state returns to active. While the upgrade is in progress
column17: the pool's currentOSVersion reflects the OS version that nodes are upgrading from
column18: and targetOSVersion reflects the OS version that nodes are upgrading to. Once the upgrade is complete
column19: currentOSVersion is updated to reflect the OS version now running on all nodes. This operation can only be invoked on pools created with the cloudServiceConfiguration property."

column17: the pool's currentOSVersion reflects the OS version that nodes are upgrading from

column13: or a page blob. If the destination blob already exists
column14: it must be of the  same blob type as the source blob. Any existing destination blob will be  overwritten. The destination blob cannot be modified while a copy operation  is in progress.  When copying from a page blob
column15: the Blob service creates a destination page  blob of the source blob's length
column16: initially containing all zeroes. Then  the source page ranges are enumerated

column12: any tasks running on that node are removed from the node and returned to the queue to be rerun later (or on a different compute node). The node will be unavailable until the upgrade is complete. This operation results in temporarily reduced pool capacity as nodes are taken out of service to be upgraded. Although the Batch service tries to avoid upgrading all compute nodes at the same time
column13: it does not guarantee to do this (particularly on small pools); therefore
column14: the pool may be temporarily unavailable to run tasks. When this operation runs
column15: the pool state changes to upgrading. When all compute nodes have finished upgrading
column16: the pool state returns to active. While the upgrade is in progress
column17: the pool's currentOSVersion reflects the OS version that nodes are upgrading from
column18: and targetOSVersion reflects the OS version that nodes are upgrading to. Once the upgrade is complete
column19: currentOSVersion is updated to reflect the OS version now running on all nodes. This operation can only be invoked on pools created with the cloudServiceConfiguration property."]

samples: [u'Deletes the specified table and any data it contains.  When a table is successfully deleted
column11: it is immediately marked for deletion  and is no longer accessible to clients. The table is later removed from  the Table service during garbage collection.  Note that deleting a table is likely to take at least 40 seconds to complete.  If an operation is attempted against the table while it was being deleted
column12: an :class:`AzureConflictHttpError` will be thrown.'
column13: u'Deletes the specified queue and any messages it contains.  When a queue is successfully deleted

Note that deleting a queue is likely to take at least 40 seconds to complete.  If an operation is attempted against the queue while it was being deleted
column15: an :class:`AzureConflictHttpError` will be thrown.']

samples: [u'Updates the visibility timeout of a message. You can also use this operation to update the contents of a message.  This operation can be used to continually extend the invisibility of a  queue message. This functionality can be useful if you want a worker role  to "lease" a queue message. For example
column11: if a worker role calls get_messages  and recognizes that it needs more time to process a message
column12: it can  continually extend the message\'s invisibility until it is processed. If  the worker role were to fail during processing
column13: eventually the message  would become visible again and another worker role could process it.  If the key-encryption-key field is set on the local service object
column14: this method will encrypt the content before uploading.']

samples: [u"Reactivates a task
column11: allowing it to run again even if its retry count has been exhausted.  Reactivation makes a task eligible to be retried again up to its maximum retry count. The task's state is changed to active. As the task is no longer in the completed state
column12: any previous exit code or failure information is no longer available after reactivation. Each time a task is reactivated
column13: its retry count is reset to 0. Reactivation will fail for tasks that are not completed or that previously completed successfully (with an exit code of 0). Additionally
column14: it will fail if the job has completed (or is terminating or deleting)."]
